#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:1
msgid "Concurrent Execution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:3
msgid ""
"You know how to describe GPU work with `DeviceOperation`, compose multi-"
"stage pipelines with `and_then` and `zip!`, and let the scheduling policy "
"assign streams. Now comes the payoff: running multiple pipelines **at the "
"same time**. This chapter walks through the `async_mlp` example end to end, "
"showing how Tokio tasks, the round-robin scheduler, and Rust's ownership "
"model come together to process four batches concurrently on one GPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:11
msgid ""
"[CUDA Programming Guide -- Multi-Device System](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/"
"cuda-programming-guide/#multi-device-system) for CUDA's rules on multi-GPU "
"contexts, peer access, and cross-device memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:15
msgid "The scenario"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:17
msgid ""
"You are running a three-layer MLP forward pass: **GEMM** (matrix multiply), "
"**MatVec** (matrix-vector product), and **ReLU** (activation). You have two "
"weight matrices loaded on the GPU and four batches of input data to process. "
"Each batch is independent -- batch 0 does not depend on batch 1 -- but they "
"all share the same weights."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:27
msgid ""
"Four MLP forward passes running concurrently. Top: shared weights uploaded "
"once as `Arc<DeviceBox>`, cloned cheaply into each batch. Middle: the GPU "
"timeline — round-robin distributes batches across four streams, and the "
"staggered pipelines overlap. Bottom: sequential processing takes ~4× the "
"time of one batch; concurrent processing takes ~1.3× if the GPU has spare "
"SMs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:34
msgid "The sequential approach processes one batch at a time:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:36
msgid ""
"Batch 0:  ████ GEMM ████ MatVec ██ ReLU █ D2H █\n"
"                                                  Batch 1:  ████ GEMM "
"████ ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:41
msgid "The concurrent approach overlaps them across streams:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:43
msgid ""
"Stream 0:  ████ GEMM ████ MatVec ██ ReLU █ D2H █\n"
"Stream 1:    ████ GEMM ████ MatVec ██ ReLU █ D2H █\n"
"Stream 2:      ████ GEMM ████ MatVec ██ ReLU █ D2H █\n"
"Stream 3:        ████ GEMM ████ MatVec ██ ReLU █ D2H █\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:50
msgid ""
"If the GPU has enough SMs to run multiple kernels simultaneously, the "
"overlapped version finishes significantly faster. And because each pipeline "
"is a single `and_then` chain on one stream, stages within a batch are still "
"strictly ordered -- no cross-stream synchronization needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:55
msgid "Step 1: Initialize the runtime"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:57
msgid ""
"Everything starts with `init_device_contexts`. This creates the CUDA "
"context, sets up the scheduling policy (round-robin with four streams by "
"default), and makes the thread-local state available for `.sync()` and `."
"await`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:61
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::device_context::init_device_contexts;\n"
"\n"
"#[tokio::main]\n"
"async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {\n"
"    init_device_contexts(0, 1)?;\n"
"    let module = kernels::load_async(0)?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:70
msgid ""
"The embedded module is loaded through the thread-local async context. The "
"typed module handle can be cloned cheaply into each batch pipeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:73
msgid "Step 2: Upload shared weights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:75
msgid ""
"The model has two weight matrices: W0 (DIM x DIM) and W1 (DIM). Both need to "
"live on the device for the duration of all four forward passes. This is "
"where `zip!` and `.arc()` earn their keep:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:79
msgid ""
"    let w0_host: Vec<f32> = (0..DIM * DIM)\n"
"        .map(|i| ((i % 7) as f32 - 3.0) * 0.01)\n"
"        .collect();\n"
"    let w1_host: Vec<f32> = (0..DIM)\n"
"        .map(|i| ((i % 5) as f32 - 2.0) * 0.01)\n"
"        .collect();\n"
"\n"
"    let (w0, w1): (Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>, Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>) = zip!(\n"
"        h2d(w0_host).arc(),\n"
"        h2d(w1_host).arc()\n"
"    ).await?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:93
msgid ""
"`zip!` bundles two independent H2D transfers into one operation. `.arc()` "
"wraps each result in `Arc` so the weights can be shared. `.await` schedules "
"the combined operation on one of the pool's streams and waits for it to "
"complete."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:97
msgid ""
"After this line, `w0` and `w1` are `Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>` -- cheap to "
"clone, safe to share, and pinned on the device."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:100
msgid "Step 3: Build and spawn batch pipelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:102
msgid ""
"Now the interesting part. For each batch, you build a lazy pipeline (no GPU "
"work yet) and hand it to `tokio::spawn`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:105
msgid ""
"    let num_batches = 4;\n"
"    let mut handles = vec![];\n"
"\n"
"    for batch_idx in 0..num_batches {\n"
"        let w0 = w0.clone();       // Arc clone: ~1 ns\n"
"        let w1 = w1.clone();\n"
"        let module = module.clone();\n"
"\n"
"        let batch_data: Vec<f32> = (0..DIM * DIM)\n"
"            .map(|i| ((i + batch_idx * 37) % 13) as f32 * 0.1)\n"
"            .collect();\n"
"\n"
"        let pipeline = zip!(h2d(batch_data), zeros(DIM * DIM), zeros(DIM))\n"
"            .and_then(move |(input, hidden, output)| {\n"
"                // Stage 1: GEMM — hidden = input × W0\n"
"                // ... build + finalize an owned launch, then chain with "
"and_then ...\n"
"            })\n"
"            .and_then(move |(hidden, output, w1, module)| {\n"
"                // Stage 2: MatVec — output = hidden × W1\n"
"                // ...\n"
"            })\n"
"            .and_then(move |(output, module)| {\n"
"                // Stage 3: ReLU — result = max(0, output)\n"
"                // ...\n"
"            })\n"
"            .and_then(d2h);  // Stage 4: copy result to host\n"
"\n"
"        handles.push(tokio::spawn(pipeline.into_future()));\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:137
msgid "Let's unpack what happens here:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:139
msgid ""
"**`pipeline` is a `DeviceOperation`.** It describes the entire forward pass "
"but performs no GPU work. Building it is pure host-side computation -- "
"allocating closures and structs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:143
msgid ""
"**`.into_future()` converts it to a `DeviceFuture`.** This triggers the "
"scheduling policy, which picks a stream. Batch 0 gets stream 0, batch 1 gets "
"stream 1, and so on -- round-robin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:147
msgid ""
"**`tokio::spawn` hands the future to the Tokio runtime.** The runtime will "
"poll it when the executor has capacity. On the first poll, the pipeline's "
"`execute()` runs, submitting all the GPU work to the assigned stream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:151
msgid ""
"**The runtime is free.** After the first poll, the task is parked. The GPU "
"is crunching numbers on four streams simultaneously. No host thread sits "
"waiting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:155
msgid ""
"**When the GPU finishes** a pipeline's work, the `cuLaunchHostFunc` callback "
"fires, waking the corresponding Tokio task. The runtime re-polls it, "
"delivering the `Vec<f32>` result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:159
msgid "Step 4: Collect results"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:161
msgid ""
"    for (i, handle) in handles.into_iter().enumerate() {\n"
"        let result: Vec<f32> = handle.await??;\n"
"        println!(\"Batch {}: {} elements, first 4 = {:?}\",\n"
"            i, result.len(), &result[..4]);\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:169
msgid ""
"The double `?` unwraps two layers: the outer `JoinError` (in case the Tokio "
"task panicked) and the inner `DeviceError` (in case GPU work failed). In a "
"production system you would handle these separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:173
msgid "`.await` vs `.sync()` vs `tokio::spawn`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:175
msgid "Having seen all three in action, here is when to reach for each:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:177
msgid ""
"**`.sync()`** blocks the calling thread until the GPU finishes. Use it in "
"scripts, tests, and anywhere you do not have an async runtime. Simple, no "
"ceremony, but no concurrency either -- the host thread is stuck waiting:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:181
msgid "let result = pipeline.sync()?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:185
msgid ""
"**`.await`** yields the current async task while the GPU works. Other tasks "
"on the same Tokio thread can make progress. This is better than `.sync()` "
"for throughput but still sequential within the task -- the code after `."
"await` does not run until the operation completes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:190
msgid "let result = pipeline.await?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:194
msgid ""
"**`tokio::spawn(op.into_future())`** launches the pipeline as a fully "
"independent task. The spawning code continues immediately, and the result "
"arrives later via the join handle. This is the way to achieve true "
"concurrency -- multiple pipelines running on different streams at the same "
"time:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:199
msgid ""
"let handle = tokio::spawn(pipeline.into_future());\n"
"// ... spawn more pipelines, do other work ...\n"
"let result = handle.await??;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:206
msgid ""
"For a chain of dependent operations (like the four-stage forward pass), "
"prefer `and_then` over sequential `.await`s. An `and_then` chain runs "
"entirely on one stream with zero scheduling overhead between stages. "
"Sequential `.await`s go through the scheduling policy for each operation, "
"potentially landing on different streams and requiring cross-stream "
"synchronization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:214
msgid "Ownership patterns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:216
msgid ""
"Concurrent GPU programming in Rust means Rust's ownership rules are actively "
"working for you -- and occasionally getting in your way. Here are the "
"patterns that come up repeatedly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:220
msgid "Moving data through `and_then` closures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:222
msgid ""
"Each `and_then` closure captures data by `move`. The kernel launch produces "
"`()`, so you need to explicitly carry forward the buffers the next stage "
"needs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:225
msgid ""
"launch_gemm(input, hidden, w0)\n"
"    .and_then(move |()| {\n"
"        // input is consumed by the kernel. hidden and module survive\n"
"        // because they were captured but not consumed.\n"
"        value((hidden, output, w1, module))\n"
"    })\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:234
msgid ""
"The closure returns a `Value` containing a tuple of everything the next "
"stage needs. This tuple is the \"baton\" passed between stages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:237
msgid "Sharing immutable data with `Arc`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:239
msgid ""
"Model weights, lookup tables, and other immutable data shared across "
"pipelines should be wrapped in `Arc`. The `.arc()` combinator does this "
"automatically for a `DeviceOperation`'s output. For data you already have, "
"`Arc::new()` works:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:243
msgid ""
"let weights = h2d(weight_data).arc().await?;  // Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>\n"
"for batch in batches {\n"
"    let w = weights.clone();  // cheap reference-count bump\n"
"    tokio::spawn(forward_pass(batch, w).into_future());\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:251
msgid "Keeping device memory alive"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:253
msgid ""
"A `DeviceBox` must stay alive until the GPU is done using it. In `and_then` "
"chains this is automatic -- the closure owns the `DeviceBox`, and it lives "
"until the next stage takes it. The danger is `with_context` closures where "
"you perform an async copy and the `DeviceBox` might be dropped before the "
"copy completes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:258
msgid ""
"fn d2h(dev: DeviceBox<[f32]>) -> impl DeviceOperation<Output = Vec<f32>> {\n"
"    with_context(move |ctx| {\n"
"        let stream = ctx.get_cuda_stream();\n"
"        let mut host = vec![0.0f32; dev.len()];\n"
"        unsafe {\n"
"            memcpy_dtoh_async(\n"
"                host.as_mut_ptr(), dev.cu_deviceptr(),\n"
"                dev.len() * std::mem::size_of::<f32>(),\n"
"                stream.cu_stream(),\n"
"            ).unwrap();\n"
"        }\n"
"        // dev is captured by the closure and lives until the closure "
"returns.\n"
"        // The stream will synchronize before the result is consumed,\n"
"        // so the async copy completes before dev is dropped.\n"
"        value(host)\n"
"    })\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:278
msgid ""
"The key: `dev` is captured by the `move` closure and is not dropped until "
"the closure returns. Since the stream synchronizes before the `DeviceFuture` "
"delivers the result, the async copy finishes before `dev` is freed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:284
msgid "Error handling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:286
msgid ""
"Errors from GPU work propagate through the `Result` chain just like any Rust "
"code. When running concurrent batches, you typically want to continue "
"processing even if one batch fails:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:290
msgid ""
"for (i, handle) in handles.into_iter().enumerate() {\n"
"    match handle.await {\n"
"        Ok(Ok(result)) => {\n"
"            println!(\"Batch {i}: {} elements\", result.len());\n"
"        }\n"
"        Ok(Err(device_err)) => {\n"
"            eprintln!(\"Batch {i}: GPU error: {device_err}\");\n"
"        }\n"
"        Err(join_err) => {\n"
"            eprintln!(\"Batch {i}: task panicked: {join_err}\");\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:306
msgid ""
"The three arms correspond to: success, a CUDA driver or scheduling error (e."
"g., out-of-memory, invalid launch config), and a Tokio task panic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:309
msgid "Multi-device execution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:311
msgid ""
"For systems with multiple GPUs, pass a higher device count to "
"`init_device_contexts`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:314
msgid ""
"init_device_contexts(0, 2)?;  // default device 0, capacity for 2 devices\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:318
msgid ""
"This sets the default device to GPU 0 and prepares the thread-local map for "
"two devices. Each device's CUDA context, scheduling policy, and stream pool "
"are created lazily on first use. All policy-driven operations (`.sync()`, `."
"await`) use the default device unless you explicitly target a different one. "
"The `ExecutionContext` carries the device ID, so operations on GPU 0 never "
"interfere with streams on GPU 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md:326
msgid ""
"Multi-device programming requires attention to memory placement. A "
"`DeviceBox` allocated on GPU 0 is not accessible from GPU 1 unless peer "
"access is enabled. Use `with_context` to check `ctx.get_device_id()` when "
"building device-specific operations."
msgstr ""

